{{Use Australian English|date=July 2018}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}
The '''Moseley Royal Commission''', officially titled the '''''Royal Commission Appointed to Investigate, Report and Advise Upon Matters in Relation to the Condition and Treatment of Aborigines''''' was a [[Royal Commission]] established by the [[Government of Western Australia]] in 1934 to hear evidence regarding the treatment of [[Indigenous Australians|Aboriginal people]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article37714481 |title=With the Aborigines Commission in the North. |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]] |location=Perth |date=12 July 1934 |accessdate=19 January 2013 |page=2 Supplement: Regular supplement – 'Pictorial section' |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==A. O. Neville==
The Royal Commission was to examine proposals to extend the powers of [[A. O. Neville]], the "[[Protector of Aborigines|Chief Protector of Aborigines]]", and the social policy of removal of children from their parents. Agitation by critics and the resulting media coverage in London<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32862235 | title=Commissioner's Report. | via=National Library of Australia | date=27 June 1935 | accessdate=19 January 2013 | newspaper=[[The West Australian]] | location=Perth | page=19}}</ref> and locally<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32807062 | title=Welfare of Aborigines. | via=National Library of Australia | date=17 October 1934 | accessdate=19 January 2013 | newspaper=[[The West Australian]] | location=Perth | page=11}}</ref> had brought attention to the Native Administration Act 1905–1936 (WA) Amendment(1911) and to actions by Neville.

A series of submissions detailing accusations of child slavery, abuse and mistreatment and the evidence was given by mothers of the removed children. The commission produced a report citing problems with the policy, but concluding to continue with the recommendations of Neville.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Western Australia. Royal Commission Appointed to Investigate, Report and Advise Upon Matters in Relation to the Condition and Treatment of Aborigines | author2=Moseley, Henry Doyle | title=Report of the Royal Commissioner appointed to investigate, report, and advise upon matters in relation to the condition and treatment of Aborigines | publication-date=1935 | publisher=Fred. Wm. Simpson, Government Printer | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/27179059 | accessdate=19 January 2013 }}</ref>

